[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference derives the posterior probability as a consequence of two antecedents: a prior probability and a "likelihood function" derived from a statistical model for the observed data.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] If that term is approximately 1, then the probability of the hypothesis given the evidence, $P(H\mid E)$ , is about ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ , about 50% likely - equally likely or not likely.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] If that term is very small, close to zero, then the probability of the hypothesis, given the evidence, $P(H\mid E)$ is close to 1 or the conditional hypothesis is quite likely.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] If that term is very large, much larger than 1, then the hypothesis, given the evidence, is quite unlikely.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian updating is widely used and computationally convenient.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] However, it is not the only updating rule that might be considered rational.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Ian Hacking noted that traditional "Dutch book" arguments did not specify Bayesian updating: they left open the possibility that non-Bayesian updating rules could avoid Dutch books.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Hacking wrote: "And neither the Dutch book argument nor any other in the personalist arsenal of proofs of the probability axioms entails the dynamic assumption.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] So the personalist requires the dynamic assumption to be Bayesian.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] It is true that in consistency a personalist could abandon the Bayesian model of learning from experience.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Indeed, there are non-Bayesian updating rules that also avoid Dutch books (as discussed in the literature on "probability kinematics") following the publication of Richard C.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Jeffrey's rule, which applies Bayes' rule to the case where the evidence itself is assigned a probability.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The additional hypotheses needed to uniquely require Bayesian updating have been deemed to be substantial, complicated, and unsatisfactory.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] If evidence is simultaneously used to update belief over a set of exclusive and exhaustive propositions, Bayesian inference may be thought of as acting on this belief distribution as a whole.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Suppose a process is generating independent and identically distributed events $E_{n},\ n=1,2,3,\ldots$ , but the probability distribution is unknown.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Let the event space $\Omega$ represent the current state of belief for this process.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Each model is represented by event $M_{m}$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The conditional probabilities $P(E_{n}\mid M_{m})$ are specified to define the models. $P(M_{m})$ is the degree of belief in $M_{m}$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Before the first inference step, $\{P(M_{m})\}$ is a set of *initial prior probabilities*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] These must sum to 1, but are otherwise arbitrary.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Suppose that the process is observed to generate $E\in \{E_{n}\}$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] For each $M\in \{M_{m}\}$ , the prior $P(M)$ is updated to the posterior $P(M\mid E)$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Upon observation of further evidence, this procedure may be repeated.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] By parameterizing the space of models, the belief in all models may be updated in a single step.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The distribution of belief over the model space may then be thought of as a distribution of belief over the parameter space.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The distributions in this section are expressed as continuous, represented by probability densities, as this is the usual situation.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The technique is, however, equally applicable to discrete distributions.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Let the vector ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ span the parameter space.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Let the initial prior distribution over ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ be $p({\boldsymbol {\theta }}\mid {\boldsymbol {\alpha }})$ , where ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ is a set of parameters to the prior itself, or *hyperparameters*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Let $\mathbf {E} =(e_{1},\dots ,e_{n})$ be a sequence of independent and identically distributed event observations, where all $e_{i}$ are distributed as $p(e\mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ for some ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] This is expressed in words as "posterior is proportional to likelihood times prior", or sometimes as "posterior = likelihood times prior, over evidence".
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] $P_{X}^{y}(A)=E(1_{A}(X)|Y=y)$ Existence and uniqueness of the needed conditional expectation is a consequence of the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] This was formulated by Kolmogorov in his famous book from 1933.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Kolmogorov underlines the importance of conditional probability by writing "I wish to call attention to ... and especially the theory of conditional probabilities and conditional expectations ..." in the Preface.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The Bayes theorem determines the posterior distribution from the prior distribution.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Uniqueness requires continuity assumptions.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayes' theorem can be generalized to include improper prior distributions such as the uniform distribution on the real line.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Modern Markov chain Monte Carlo methods have boosted the importance of Bayes' theorem including cases with improper priors.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian theory calls for the use of the posterior predictive distribution to do predictive inference, i.e., to predict the distribution of a new, unobserved data point.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] That is, instead of a fixed point as a prediction, a distribution over possible points is returned.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Only this way is the entire posterior distribution of the parameter(s) used.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] By comparison, prediction in frequentist statistics often involves finding an optimum point estimate of the parameter(s)—e.g., by maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori estimation (MAP)—and then plugging this estimate into the formula for the distribution of a data point.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] This has the disadvantage that it does not account for any uncertainty in the value of the parameter, and hence will underestimate the variance of the predictive distribution.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In some instances, frequentist statistics can work around this problem.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] For example, confidence intervals and prediction intervals in frequentist statistics when constructed from a normal distribution with unknown mean and variance are constructed using a Student's t-distribution.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In Bayesian statistics, however, the posterior predictive distribution can always be determined exactly—or at least to an arbitrary level of precision when numerical methods are used.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Both types of predictive distributions have the form of a compound probability distribution (as does the marginal likelihood).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In fact, if the prior distribution is a conjugate prior, such that the prior and posterior distributions come from the same family, it can be seen that both prior and posterior predictive distributions also come from the same family of compound distributions.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] That is, if the model were true, the evidence would be more likely than is predicted by the current state of belief.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The reverse applies for a decrease in belief.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] If the belief does not change, ${\textstyle {\frac {P(E\mid M)}{P(E)}}=1\Rightarrow P(E\mid M)=P(E)}$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] That is, the evidence is independent of the model.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] If the model were true, the evidence would be exactly as likely as predicted by the current state of belief.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] This can be interpreted to mean that hard convictions are insensitive to counter-evidence.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The former follows directly from Bayes' theorem.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The latter can be derived by applying the first rule to the event "not M " in place of " M ", yielding "if $1-P(M)=0$ , then $1-P(M\mid E)=0$ ", from which the result immediately follows.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Consider the behaviour of a belief distribution as it is updated a large number of times with independent and identically distributed trials.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] For sufficiently nice prior probabilities, the Bernstein-von Mises theorem gives that in the limit of infinite trials, the posterior converges to a Gaussian distribution independent of the initial prior under some conditions firstly outlined and rigorously proven by Joseph L.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Doob in 1948, namely if the random variable in consideration has a finite probability space.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The more general results were obtained later by the statistician David A.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Freedman who published in two seminal research papers in 1963 and 1965 when and under what circumstances the asymptotic behaviour of posterior is guaranteed.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] His 1963 paper treats, like Doob (1949), the finite case and comes to a satisfactory conclusion.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] However, if the random variable has an infinite but countable probability space (i.e., corresponding to a die with infinite many faces) the 1965 paper demonstrates that for a dense subset of priors the Bernstein-von Mises theorem is not applicable.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In this case there is almost surely no asymptotic convergence.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Later in the 1980s and 1990s Freedman and Persi Diaconis continued to work on the case of infinite countable probability spaces.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] To summarise, there may be insufficient trials to suppress the effects of the initial choice, and especially for large (but finite) systems the convergence might be very slow.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In parameterized form, the prior distribution is often assumed to come from a family of distributions called conjugate priors.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The usefulness of a conjugate prior is that the corresponding posterior distribution will be in the same family, and the calculation may be expressed in closed form.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] It is often desired to use a posterior distribution to estimate a parameter or variable.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Several methods of Bayesian estimation select measurements of central tendency from the posterior distribution.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] For one-dimensional problems, a unique median exists for practical continuous problems.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The posterior median is attractive as a robust estimator.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] There are examples where no maximum is attained, in which case the set of MAP estimates is empty.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] There are other methods of estimation that minimize the posterior risk (expected-posterior loss) with respect to a loss function, and these are of interest to statistical decision theory using the sampling distribution (frequentist statistics).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Suppose there are two full bowls of cookies.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bowl #1 has 10 chocolate chip and 30 plain cookies, while bowl #2 has 20 of each.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Fred picks a bowl at random and then picks a cookie at random, which means that there is no reason to believe Fred treats one bowl differently from another, likewise for the cookies.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] As to how probable it is that Fred picked it out of bowl #1, that is an example of a Bayesian inference-approachable problem.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Intuitively, it seems clear that the answer should be more than a half, since there are more plain cookies in bowl #1.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The precise answer is given by Bayes' theorem.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] It is given that the bowls are identical from Fred's point of view, thus $P(H_{1})=P(H_{2})$ , and the two must add up to 1, so both are equal to 0.5.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The event E is the observation of a plain cookie.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] An archaeologist is working at a site thought to be from the medieval period, between the 11th century to the 16th century.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] However, it is uncertain exactly when in this period the site was inhabited.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Fragments of pottery are found, some of which are glazed and some of which are decorated.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] It is expected that if the site were inhabited during the early medieval period, then 1% of the pottery would be glazed and 50% of its area decorated, whereas if it had been inhabited in the late medieval period then 81% would be glazed and 5% of its area decorated.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] How confident can the archaeologist be in the date of inhabitation as fragments are unearthed?
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The degree of belief in the continuous variable C (century) is to be calculated, with the discrete set of events $\{GD,G{\bar {D}},{\bar {G}}D,{\bar {G}}{\bar {D}}\}$ as evidence.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] When a new fragment of type e is discovered, that means *more information* for the investigation and, through Bayes' theorem, an *updated* Bayesian inference towards an improved degree of belief (or confidence) in the archeologists' estimation.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] A computer simulation of the changing belief as 50 fragments are unearthed is shown on the graph.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In the simulation, the site was inhabited around 1420, or $c=15.2$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The Bernstein-von Mises theorem asserts here the asymptotic convergence to the "true" distribution because the probability space corresponding to the discrete set of events $\{GD,G{\bar {D}},{\bar {G}}D,{\bar {G}}{\bar {D}}\}$ is finite (see above section on asymptotic behaviour of the posterior).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] A decision-theoretic justification of the use of Bayesian inference was given by Abraham Wald, who proved that every unique Bayesian procedure is admissible.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Conversely, every admissible statistical procedure is either a Bayesian procedure or a limit of Bayesian procedures.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Wald characterized admissible procedures as Bayesian procedures (and limits of Bayesian procedures), making the Bayesian formalism a central technique in such areas of frequentist inference as parameter estimation, hypothesis testing, and computing confidence intervals.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian methodology also plays a role in model selection where the aim is to select one model from a set of competing models that represents most closely the underlying process that generated the observed data.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In Bayesian model comparison, the model with the highest posterior probability given the data is selected.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The posterior probability of a model depends on the evidence, or marginal likelihood, which reflects the probability that the data is generated by the model, and on the prior belief of the model.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] When two competing models are a priori considered to be equiprobable, the ratio of their posterior probabilities corresponds to the Bayes factor.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Since Bayesian model comparison is aimed on selecting the model with the highest posterior probability, this methodology is also referred to as the maximum a posteriori (MAP) selection rule or the MAP probability rule.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] While conceptually simple, Bayesian methods can be mathematically and numerically challenging.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Probabilistic programming languages (PPLs) implement functions to easily build Bayesian models together with efficient automatic inference methods.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] This helps separate the model building from the inference, allowing practitioners to focus on their specific problems and leaving PPLs to handle the computational details for them.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] See the separate Wikipedia entry on Bayesian statistics, specifically the statistical modeling section in that page.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference has applications in artificial intelligence and expert systems.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference techniques have been a fundamental part of computerized pattern recognition techniques since the late 1950s.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Recently Bayesian inference has gained popularity among the phylogenetics community for these reasons; a number of applications allow many demographic and evolutionary parameters to be estimated simultaneously.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] As applied to statistical classification, Bayesian inference has been used to develop algorithms for identifying e-mail spam.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Applications which make use of Bayesian inference for spam filtering include CRM114, DSPAM, Bogofilter, SpamAssassin, SpamBayes, Mozilla, XEAMS, and others.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Spam classification is treated in more detail in the article on the naïve Bayes classifier.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Solomonoff's Inductive inference is the theory of prediction based on observations; for example, predicting the next symbol based upon a given series of symbols.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The only assumption is that the environment follows some unknown but computable probability distribution.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] It is a formal inductive framework that combines two well-studied principles of inductive inference: Bayesian statistics and Occam's Razor.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Solomonoff's universal prior probability of any prefix *p* of a computable sequence *x* is the sum of the probabilities of all programs (for a universal computer) that compute something starting with *p*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Given some *p* and any computable but unknown probability distribution from which *x* is sampled, the universal prior and Bayes' theorem can be used to predict the yet unseen parts of *x* in optimal fashion.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference has been applied in different bioinformatics applications, including differential gene expression analysis.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference is also used in a general cancer risk model, called CIRI (Continuous Individualized Risk Index), where serial measurements are incorporated to update a Bayesian model which is primarily built from prior knowledge.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In cosmology, it is often employed with computational techniques such as Markov chain Monte Carlo(MCMC) and Nested sampling algorithm to analyse complex datasets and navigate high-dimensional parameter space.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] A notable application is to the Planck 2018 CMB data for parameter inference.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The six base cosmological parameters in Lambda-CDM model are not predicted by a theory, but rather fitted from Cosmic microwave background (CMB) data to a chosen model of cosmology (the Lambda-CDM model).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The bayesian code for cosmology `cobaya` sets up cosmological runs and interfaces cosmological likelihoods, Boltzmann code, which computes the predicted CMB anisotropies for any given set of cosmological parameters, with MCMC or nested sampler.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] This computational framework is not limited to the standard model, it is also essential for testing alternative or extended theories of cosmology, such as theories with early dark energy, or modified gravity theories introducing additional parameters beyond Lambda-CDM.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian model comparison can then be employed to calculate the evidence for competing models, providing a statistical basis to assess whether the data support them over the standard Lambda-CDM.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference can be used by jurors to coherently accumulate the evidence for and against a defendant, and to see whether, in totality, it meets their personal threshold for "beyond a reasonable doubt".
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayes' theorem is applied successively to all evidence presented, with the posterior from one stage becoming the prior for the next.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The benefit of a Bayesian approach is that it gives the juror an unbiased, rational mechanism for combining evidence.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] It may be appropriate to explain Bayes' theorem to jurors in odds form, as betting odds are more widely understood than probabilities.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Alternatively, a logarithmic approach, replacing multiplication with addition, might be easier for a jury to handle.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] If the existence of the crime is not in doubt, only the identity of the culprit, it has been suggested that the prior should be uniform over the qualifying population.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] For example, if 1,000 people could have committed the crime, the prior probability of guilt would be 1/1000.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The use of Bayes' theorem by jurors is controversial.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In the United Kingdom, a defence expert witness explained Bayes' theorem to the jury in *R v Adams*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The jury convicted, but the case went to appeal on the basis that no means of accumulating evidence had been provided for jurors who did not wish to use Bayes' theorem.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Gardner-Medwin argues that the criterion on which a verdict in a criminal trial should be based is *not* the probability of guilt, but rather the *probability of the evidence, given that the defendant is innocent* (akin to a frequentist p-value).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] He argues that if the posterior probability of guilt is to be computed by Bayes' theorem, the prior probability of guilt must be known.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] This will depend on the incidence of the crime, which is an unusual piece of evidence to consider in a criminal trial.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] – the known facts and testimony could have arisen if the defendant is guilty.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] – the known facts and testimony could have arisen if the defendant is innocent.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Gardner-Medwin argues that the jury should believe both *A* and not-*B* in order to convict.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] *A* and not-*B* implies the truth of *C*, but the reverse is not true.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] It is possible that *B* and *C* are both true, but in this case he argues that a jury should acquit, even though they know that they will be letting some guilty people go free.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Bayesian epistemology is a movement that advocates for Bayesian inference as a means of justifying the rules of inductive logic.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Karl Popper and David Miller have rejected the idea of Bayesian rationalism, i.e. using Bayes rule to make epistemological inferences: It is prone to the same vicious circle as any other justificationist epistemology, because it presupposes what it attempts to justify.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The problem considered by Bayes in Proposition 9 of his essay, "An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances", is the posterior distribution for the parameter *a* (the success rate) of the binomial distribution.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] The term 'Bayesian' refers to Thomas Bayes (1701–1761), who proved that probabilistic limits could be placed on an unknown event.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] However, it was Pierre-Simon Laplace (1749–1827) who introduced (as Principle VI) what is now called Bayes' theorem and used it to address problems in celestial mechanics, medical statistics, reliability, and jurisprudence.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Early Bayesian inference, which used uniform priors following Laplace's principle of insufficient reason, was called inverse probability (because it infers backwards from observations to parameters, or from effects to causes).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] After the 1920s, inverse probability was largely supplanted by a collection of methods that came to be called frequentist statistics.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In the 20th century, the ideas of Laplace were further developed in two different directions, giving rise to *objective* and *subjective* currents in Bayesian practice.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In the objective (or "non-informative") current, the statistical analysis depends only on the model assumed, the data analyzed, and the method assigning the prior, which differs from one objective Bayesian practitioner to another.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In the subjective (or "informative") current, the specification of the prior depends on the belief—the propositions on which the analysis is prepared to act—which can summarize information from experts, previous studies, etc.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] In the 1980s, there was a dramatic growth in research and applications of Bayesian methods, mostly attributed to the discovery of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, which removed many of the computational problems, and an increasing interest in nonstandard, complex applications.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Despite growth of Bayesian research, most undergraduate teaching is still based on frequentist statistics.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-inference] Nonetheless, Bayesian methods are widely accepted and used, such as for example in the field of machine learning.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A **Bayesian network** (also known as a **Bayes network**, **Bayes net**, **belief network**, or **decision network**) is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of variables and their conditional dependencies via a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] While it is one of several forms of causal notation, causal networks are special cases of Bayesian networks.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Bayesian networks are ideal for taking an event that occurred and predicting the likelihood that any one of several possible known causes was the contributing factor.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Efficient algorithms can perform inference and learning in Bayesian networks.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables (*e.g.* speech signals or protein sequences) are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Generalizations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Formally, Bayesian networks are directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) whose nodes represent variables in the Bayesian sense: they may be observable quantities, latent variables, unknown parameters or hypotheses.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Each edge represents a direct conditional dependency.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Any pair of nodes that are not connected (i.e. no path connects one node to the other) represent variables that are conditionally independent of each other.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Each node is associated with a probability function that takes, as input, a particular set of values for the node's parent variables, and gives (as output) the probability (or probability distribution, if applicable) of the variable represented by the node.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] For example, if m parent nodes represent m Boolean variables, then the probability function could be represented by a table of $2^{m}$ entries, one entry for each of the $2^{m}$ possible parent combinations.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Similar ideas may be applied to undirected, and possibly cyclic, graphs such as Markov networks.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Suppose we want to model the dependencies between three variables: the sprinkler (or more appropriately, its state - whether it is on or not), the presence or absence of rain and whether the grass is wet or not.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Observe that two events can cause the grass to become wet: an active sprinkler or rain.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Rain has a direct effect on the use of the sprinkler (namely that when it rains, the sprinkler usually is not active).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This situation can be modeled with a Bayesian network (shown to the right).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Each variable has two possible values, T (for true) and F (for false).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] where *G* = "Grass wet (true/false)", *S* = "Sprinkler turned on (true/false)", and *R* = "Raining (true/false)".
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Using the expansion for the joint probability function $\Pr(G,S,R)$ and the conditional probabilities from the conditional probability tables (CPTs) stated in the diagram, one can evaluate each term in the sums in the numerator and denominator.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] obtained by removing the factor $\Pr(G\mid S,R)$ from the pre-intervention distribution.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The do operator forces the value of G to be true.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] with the term $\Pr(S=T\mid R)$ removed, showing that the action affects the grass but not the rain.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] These predictions may not be feasible given unobserved variables, as in most policy evaluation problems.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The effect of the action ${\text{do}}(x)$ can still be predicted, however, whenever the back-door criterion is satisfied.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A back-door path is one that ends with an arrow into *X*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Sets that satisfy the back-door criterion are called "sufficient" or "admissible." For example, the set *Z* = *R* is admissible for predicting the effect of *S* = *T* on *G*, because *R* *d*-separates the (only) back-door path *S* ← *R* → *G*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] However, if *S* is not observed, no other set *d*-separates this path and the effect of turning the sprinkler on (*S* = *T*) on the grass (*G*) cannot be predicted from passive observations.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This reflects the fact that, lacking interventional data, the observed dependence between *S* and *G* is due to a causal connection or is spurious (apparent dependence arising from a common cause, *R*).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Using a Bayesian network can save considerable amounts of memory over exhaustive probability tables, if the dependencies in the joint distribution are sparse.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] For example, a naive way of storing the conditional probabilities of 10 two-valued variables as a table requires storage space for $2^{10}=1024$ values.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] If no variable's local distribution depends on more than three parent variables, the Bayesian network representation stores at most $10\cdot 2^{3}=80$ values.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] One advantage of Bayesian networks is that it is intuitively easier for a human to understand (a sparse set of) direct dependencies and local distributions than complete joint distributions.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Because a Bayesian network is a complete model for its variables and their relationships, it can be used to answer probabilistic queries about them.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] For example, the network can be used to update knowledge of the state of a subset of variables when other variables (the *evidence* variables) are observed.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This process of computing the *posterior* distribution of variables given evidence is called probabilistic inference.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The posterior gives a universal sufficient statistic for detection applications, when choosing values for the variable subset that minimize some expected loss function, for instance the probability of decision error.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A Bayesian network can thus be considered a mechanism for automatically applying Bayes' theorem to complex problems.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] All of these methods have complexity that is exponential in the network's treewidth.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The most common approximate inference algorithms are importance sampling, stochastic MCMC simulation, mini-bucket elimination, loopy belief propagation, generalized belief propagation and variational methods.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In order to fully specify the Bayesian network and thus fully represent the joint probability distribution, it is necessary to specify for each node *X* the probability distribution for *X* conditional upon *X*'s parents.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The distribution of *X* conditional upon its parents may have any form.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] It is common to work with discrete or Gaussian distributions since that simplifies calculations.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Sometimes only constraints on distribution are known; one can then use the principle of maximum entropy to determine a single distribution, the one with the greatest entropy given the constraints.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Often these conditional distributions include parameters that are unknown and must be estimated from data, e.g., via the maximum likelihood approach.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Direct maximization of the likelihood (or of the posterior probability) is often complex given unobserved variables.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A classical approach to this problem is the expectation-maximization algorithm, which alternates computing expected values of the unobserved variables conditional on observed data, with maximizing the complete likelihood (or posterior) assuming that previously computed expected values are correct.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Under mild regularity conditions, this process converges on maximum likelihood (or maximum posterior) values for parameters.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A more fully Bayesian approach to parameters is to treat them as additional unobserved variables and to compute a full posterior distribution over all nodes conditional upon observed data, then to integrate out the parameters.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This approach can be expensive and lead to large dimension models, making classical parameter-setting approaches more tractable.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In the simplest case, a Bayesian network is specified by an expert and is then used to perform inference.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In other applications, the task of defining the network is too complex for humans.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In this case, the network structure and the parameters of the local distributions must be learned from data.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Automatically learning the graph structure of a Bayesian network (BN) is a challenge pursued within machine learning.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The first 2 represent the same dependencies ( X and Z are independent given Y ) and are, therefore, indistinguishable.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The collider, however, can be uniquely identified, since X and Z are marginally independent and all other pairs are dependent.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Thus, while the *skeletons* (the graphs stripped of arrows) of these three triplets are identical, the directionality of the arrows is partially identifiable.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The same distinction applies when X and Z have common parents, except that one must first condition on those parents.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Algorithms have been developed to systematically determine the skeleton of the underlying graph and, then, orient all arrows whose directionality is dictated by the conditional independences observed.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] An alternative method of structural learning uses optimization-based search.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] It requires a scoring function and a search strategy.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A common scoring function is posterior probability of the structure given the training data, like the BIC or the BDeu.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The time requirement of an exhaustive search returning a structure that maximizes the score is superexponential in the number of variables.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A local search strategy makes incremental changes aimed at improving the score of the structure.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A global search algorithm like Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) can avoid getting trapped in local minima.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Finding a structure that maximizes the mutual information, typically by restricting the parent candidate set to *k* nodes or by finding an optimal *k* on a node-per-node basis, is a technique that consistently achieves high scores on benchmark datasets.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] A particularly fast method for exact BN learning is to cast the problem as an optimization problem, and solve it using integer programming.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Acyclicity constraints are added to the integer program (IP) during solving in the form of cutting planes.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Such method can handle problems with up to 100 variables.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In order to deal with problems with thousands of variables, a different approach is necessary.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] One is to first sample one ordering, and then find the optimal BN structure with respect to that ordering.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This implies working on the search space of the possible orderings, which is convenient as it is smaller than the space of network structures.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Multiple orderings are then sampled and evaluated.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This method has been proven to be the best available in literature when the number of variables is huge.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Another method consists of focusing on the sub-class of decomposable models, for which the MLE have a closed form.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] It is then possible to discover a consistent structure for hundreds of variables.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Learning Bayesian networks with bounded treewidth is necessary to allow exact, tractable inference, since the worst-case inference complexity is exponential in the treewidth k (under the exponential time hypothesis).
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Yet, as a global property of the graph, it considerably increases the difficulty of the learning process.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In this context it is possible to use K-tree for effective learning.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Given data $x\,\!$ and parameter $\theta$ , a simple Bayesian analysis starts with a prior probability (*prior*) $p(\theta )$ and likelihood $p(x\mid \theta )$ to compute a posterior probability $p(\theta \mid x)\propto p(x\mid \theta )p(\theta )$ .
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Often the prior on $\theta$ depends in turn on other parameters $\varphi$ that are not mentioned in the likelihood.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This is the simplest example of a *hierarchical Bayes model*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The process may be repeated; for example, the parameters $\varphi$ may depend in turn on additional parameters $\psi \,\!$ , which require their own prior.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Eventually the process must terminate, with priors that do not depend on unmentioned parameters.
