[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In general, learning a Bayesian network from data is known to be NP-hard.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This is due in part to the combinatorial explosion of enumerating DAGs as the number of variables increases.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] Developing a Bayesian network often begins with creating a DAG *G* such that *X* satisfies the local Markov property with respect to *G*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The conditional probability distributions of each variable given its parents in *G* are assessed.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] In many cases, in particular in the case where the variables are discrete, if the joint distribution of *X* is the product of these conditional distributions, then *X* is a Bayesian network with respect to *G*.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The Markov blanket of a node is the set of nodes consisting of its parents, its children, and any other parents of its children.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] The Markov blanket renders the node independent of the rest of the network; the joint distribution of the variables in the Markov blanket of a node is sufficient knowledge for calculating the distribution of the node.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] *X* is a Bayesian network with respect to *G* if every node is conditionally independent of all other nodes in the network, given its Markov blanket.
[src:probabilistic-programming/bayesian-network] This definition can be made more general by defining the "d"-separation of two nodes, where d stands for directional.
